    "narrative": "The Austin Waves lineup is anchored by **Kyle Tucker** (77.0) and **Jackson Merrill** (75.1), our top two plays for the day. **Kyle Tucker** benefits from a favorable matchup against Leiter, where his high xwOBA and platoon advantage provide a clear ceiling. Meanwhile, **Jackson Merrill** is a high-upside play against Feltner; his score is significantly boosted by an favorable wind forecast and a slow delivery from the opposing pitcher, which maximizes our stolen base potential\u2014a critical priority for this roster. **Gunnar Henderson** (70.9) rounds out our elite tier, as his leadoff status and dynamic platoon edge overcome a tough matchup against Logan Webb, though we are wary of Webb\u2019s ability to suppress the running game.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Marcell Ozuna** (52.1), who narrowly missed the cutoff. While his raw hitting profile is potent, his efficiency score was dragged down by a mediocre matchup against Cabrera and the relative strength of our middle-of-the-pack starters like **Liam Hicks** (53.5) and **Jorge Polanco** (54.1), who hold slightly better positional and platoon-adjusted projections today. We are also monitoring **Nolan Schanuel** (64.7), who offers the strongest value outside the top trio due to a soft matchup against Williamson; his elevated score makes him a cornerstone of today\u2019s offensive floor.\n\nRisk management remains a primary concern regarding our stolen base targets. Both **Luis Robert Jr.** (62.0) and **Gunnar Henderson** face opposing catchers with elite pop times, which slightly dampens our aggressive baserunning expectations despite their strong hitting projections. Furthermore, **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (52.9) is starting against a tough arm in Ryan, and while he remains in the lineup, we will be tracking his early-game contact quality closely. With **Coby Mayo** and **Josh Jung** falling below the 40.0 efficiency floor, we are comfortable keeping the bench restricted 